    (1) [cite_start]Fifth root of 13 [cite: 46]
    (2) [cite_start]Sixth root of 9 [cite: 47]
    (3) [cite_start]Square root of 256 [cite: 48]
    (4) [cite_start]Cube root of 17 [cite: 49]
    (5) [cite_start]Eighth root of 100 [cite: 50]
    (6) [cite_start]Seventh root of 30 [cite: 51]

2.  [cite_start]**Write in the form '$n^{th}$ root of a' in each of the following numbers.** [cite: 52]
    (1) [cite_start]$(81)^{\frac{1}{4}}$ [cite: 53]
    (2) [cite_start]$49^{\frac{1}{2}}$ [cite: 54]
    (3) [cite_start]$(15)^{\frac{1}{5}}$ [cite: 55, 56]
    (4) [cite_start]$(512)^{\frac{1}{9}}$ [cite: 57]
    (5) [cite_start]$100^{\frac{1}{19}}$ [cite: 58]
    (6) [cite_start]$(6)^{\frac{1}{7}}$ [cite: 67]

---
[cite_start]**(II) The meaning of numbers, having index in the rational form $\frac{m}{n}$.** [cite: 59]

[cite_start]We can get two meanings from a number like $a^{\frac{m}{n}}$: [cite: 78, 79]
1.  [cite_start]$a^{\frac{m}{n}} = (a^m)^{\frac{1}{n}}$ means '$n^{th}$ root of $m^{th}$ power of a'. [cite: 80]
2.  [cite_start]$a^{\frac{m}{n}} = (a^{\frac{1}{n}})^m$ means '$m^{th}$ power of $n^{th}$ root of a'. [cite: 81]

For example, for $8^{\frac{2}{3}}$:
* [cite_start]$(8^2)^{\frac{1}{3}}$ means 'cube root of the square of 8'. [cite: 73]
* [cite_start]$(8^{\frac{1}{3}})^2$ means 'square of the cube root of 8'. [cite: 73]

